    <section>
        <h2>Ingredients</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>1 medium Napa cabbage</li>
            <li>1/4 cup sea salt</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon grated ginger</li>
            <li>3 cloves garlic, minced</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon sugar</li>
            <li>3 tablespoons fish sauce (or soy sauce for vegan version)</li>
            <li>3 tablespoons Korean red pepper flakes (Gochugaru)</li>
            <li>3 green onions, chopped</li>
            <li>1 medium carrot, julienned</li>
            <li>1 daikon radish, julienned</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Tags</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Kimchi</li>
            <li>Korean</li>
            <li>Fermented</li>
            <li>Vegan</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Instructions</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Cut the Napa cabbage in half lengthwise and then into thirds. Rub sea salt between the leaves and place them in a large bowl. Let it sit for about 2 hours, turning occasionally.</li>
            <li>Rinse the cabbage under cold water to remove excess salt. Squeeze out any excess water and set aside.</li>
            <li>In a bowl, mix grated ginger, minced garlic, sugar, fish sauce (or soy sauce), and Korean red pepper flakes to make the kimchi paste.</li>
            <li>Add chopped green onions, julienned carrot, and julienned daikon radish to the paste. Mix well until the vegetables are coated with the paste.</li>
            <li>Spread the kimchi paste mixture between the leaves of the cabbage, making sure each leaf is coated.</li>
            <li>Place the kimchi into a clean, airtight jar, pressing it down to remove air bubbles. Leave some space at the top of the jar to allow for expansion.</li>
            <li>Seal the jar and let it ferment at room temperature for 1-5 days, depending on your desired level of fermentation. Burp the jar daily to release gases.</li>
            <li>Once fermented, store the kimchi in the refrigerator. It will continue to develop flavor over time.</li>
            <li>Enjoy your homemade Kimchi!</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

